fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Let C and D be precategories, and let F,G\colon  C\to  D be two functors from C to D. A natural transformation \alpha \colon  F\to  G is given by a family of arrows \alpha _\bullet \colon \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}D
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen Fx,Gx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 equipped with a (necessarily unique) naturality datum \alpha _f\colon  \alpha _y\circ  Ff = Gf\circ  \alpha _x for each f\colon  x\to  y.

